The Milan policemen who shot dead the suspect in the Berlin Christmas market truck attack were carrying out a routine patrol and had no information that he was in Milan, the city&#8217;s police chief said on Friday.The suspect, Tunisian Anis Amri, was shot at around 3 am (0200 GMT) by two officers who spotted him standing near a train station in a Milan suburb.&#8220;We had no intelligence that he could be in Milan,&#8221; police chief Antonio De Iesu said at a news conference. &#8220;They had no perception that it could be him otherwise they would have been much more cautious.&#8221;-Reuters